<section class="section section-black">
  <div class="section-inner">
    <div class="section-num">03 — Technology</div>
    <h2 class="section-title">F&amp;P Innovation — And What Breaks Differently</h2>
    <p class="section-lead">Fisher &amp; Paykel's products require specific service knowledge because they work differently from standard appliances. Here's what every F&amp;P technician needs to understand.</p>

    <div class="features-2col">
      <ul class="features-list">
        <li><strong>DishDrawer Independent Zones</strong> — Each drawer in a Double DishDrawer is a complete, independent dishwasher: its own pump, water inlet valve, spray arm, and control board. When one drawer fails and the other works normally, the diagnosis stays within that drawer's zone. We never swap components between drawers without confirming the fault zone first.</li>
        <li><strong>DishDrawer Slide Mechanism</strong> — The drawer slide and latch seal system operates under wash pressure — it must seal tightly during the cycle and release smoothly after. The latch seal degrades faster than a standard door gasket because it cycles under dynamic load. We inspect the slide rails, the latch mechanism, and the door seal on every DishDrawer service call.</li>
        <li><strong>CoolDrawer Mode Control Circuit</strong> — The five-mode system uses a dedicated temperature control circuit that sets the compressor target for each mode. Mode-specific failures — where freezer mode works but wine mode drifts — point to the temperature sensor calibration for that mode range, not the compressor. We test mode-by-mode before recommending parts.</li>
        <li><strong>DCS Dual-Flow Burner</strong> — DCS's patented dual-flow burner delivers flame from both the top and sides of the burner cap, creating more even heat distribution than standard single-flow burners. The geometry of the dual-flow configuration means igniters are positioned differently — OEM DCS igniters are required for correct spark gap alignment.</li>
        <li><strong>SmartDrive Motor (GWL Washers)</strong> — F&amp;P GWL series top-loaders use a Phase 7 direct-drive SmartDrive motor with no belt. Failure presents as a controller fault code rather than the mechanical symptoms of belt failure. SmartDrive motor replacement requires F&amp;P-specific diagnostic tools to confirm the motor vs. the controller.</li>
        <li><strong>ActiveSmart Adaptive Cooling</strong> — The ActiveSmart system learns usage patterns and pre-cools before peak usage periods. When the sensor module fails, it reverts to fixed-cycle operation that doesn't adapt — cold spots near vents and warmer areas toward the front become permanent. Sensor replacement restores adaptive function.</li>
      </ul>
      <div>
        <div class="tip-block" style="background:#0a1015; border-color:#3a7bd5; margin-top:0">
          <div class="tip-label" style="color:#6aabff">🔥 DCS — Commercial Power, Home Installation</div>
          <div class="tip-text" style="color:#bbb">DCS ranges were designed from the ground up for serious cooking — 25,000+ BTU dual-flow burners, heavy-duty continuous grates that span the full cooktop width, and an infrared broiler that operates at professional temperatures. In LA, DCS shows up in kitchens where the homeowner actually cooks seriously — not just owns impressive equipment. When a DCS range needs service, it needs a technician who understands the dual-flow burner geometry and the infrared system. We service DCS ranges with the same care we give to Wolf and Viking.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="tip-block tip-blue" style="margin-top:16px">
          <div class="tip-label">💧 Gas on Glass — Service Considerations</div>
          <div class="tip-text">F&amp;P's "Gas on Glass" cooktop puts gas burners on a sealed glass surface. The glass creates a different thermal environment for the igniter — heat dissipates differently than on cast iron. Scale from cooking liquids also accumulates around the burner base differently on glass. We clean the burner area with glass-safe tools and use OEM Gas on Glass igniter assemblies that account for the glass-mounted geometry.</div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="section">
  <div class="section-inner">
    <div class="section-num">04 — Common Problems</div>
    <h2 class="section-title">Most Common Fisher &amp; Paykel Failures in Los Angeles</h2>

    <div class="problems-grid">
      <div class="problem-card">
        <div class="problem-title">🍽️ DishDrawer Not Draining One Drawer</div>
        <div class="problem-cause">Drain pump impeller blocked in that drawer's independent drain circuit — food debris or a piece of broken crockery lodged in the pump. Because each drawer is independent, the other drawer may continue working normally. We diagnose per-drawer — clearing the pump in the affected zone, not replacing system-wide components.</div>
        <span class="problem-tag tag-drawer">DishDrawer</span>
      </div>

      <div class="problem-card">
        <div class="problem-title">🍽️ DishDrawer Latch Not Sealing</div>
        <div class="problem-cause">Drawer latch seal degradation — the seal that holds the drawer closed under wash pressure loses its compression over time. Water seeps past the latch during the cycle, triggering an overflow protection fault. We replace the latch seal assembly with OEM F&amp;P parts. This is a routine wear item on high-use DishDrawers after 4–6 years.</div>
        <span class="problem-tag tag-drawer">DishDrawer</span>
      </div>

      <div class="problem-card">
        <div class="problem-title">❄️ CoolDrawer Not Reaching Freezer Mode</div>
        <div class="problem-cause">Temperature sensor drift in the low-end range — the sensor reads the drawer temperature as colder than it actually is, causing the compressor to run less than needed. The unit may maintain fridge or wine modes correctly while failing at freezer target. Mode-specific sensor testing confirms this without compressor work.</div>
        <span class="problem-tag tag-common">Most Common</span>
      </div>

      <div class="problem-card">
        <div class="problem-title">🔥 DCS Dual-Flow Igniter Failure</div>
        <div class="problem-cause">The dual-flow burner's igniter position is geometry-specific — positioned to spark between both the top and side flame ports. Coastal LA salt air accelerates ceramic corrosion on DCS igniters faster than inland properties. OEM DCS igniters maintain the correct spark gap geometry; generic igniters positioned incorrectly result in incomplete ignition.</div>
        <span class="problem-tag tag-dcs">DCS Range</span>
      </div>

      <div class="problem-card">
        <div class="problem-title">🌀 SmartDrive Washer Fault Code</div>
        <div class="problem-cause">SmartDrive motor or motor controller fault — displayed as an error code rather than mechanical symptoms. The direct-drive motor fails differently from belt-drive washers; there's no belt slippage or noise before the fault code appears. We use F&amp;P-specific diagnostics to confirm motor vs. controller failure before ordering parts.</div>
        <span class="problem-tag tag-common">Most Common</span>
      </div>

      <div class="problem-card">
        <div class="problem-title">🧠 ActiveSmart Temperature Fluctuation</div>
        <div class="problem-cause">ActiveSmart sensor module failure — the refrigerator loses its adaptive cooling and reverts to fixed-cycle operation. Cold spots near vents and warmer zones at the front become permanent. LA's hot ambient conditions (especially Valley locations) stress the ActiveSmart system more than moderate climates. Sensor module replacement restores adaptive function.</div>
        <span class="problem-tag tag-la">LA Environment</span>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

